@Carreau in terms of inheritance, classmethods work with `super`:

```python
class A(object):
    @classmethod
    def f(cls):
        print(cls)

class B(A):
    def f(self):
        super(B, self).f()
```

Thanks for splitting up your patch a  bit and thanks for this patch. I recall Spotify wanted exactly this too (at least the max aggreation) and many other will find it useful too. Even VNG I think. But for this to be useful the API must be easy to use. In this post I'll focus on grinding on the API.

-----

So I am putting on my critiquing hat for a moment. Because I find the API
quite cumbersome. So let me take an example of a Task I would like to batchify (mostly stolen from your tests :)).
I start with my unbatched task looking like this. This will all be pseudo code.

    class OrigTask(Task):
        val = luigi.IntParameter()

        def run(self):
            my_api.update(self.val)

        def complete(self):
            return self.val in my_api

