Traitlets version of the progress bar shown above:

```python
import os
from binascii import hexlify
import time
import traitlets

from traitlets import observe, Int, HasTraits

class ProgressBar(HasTraits):
    capacity = Integer(100, help="capacity for progress")
    progress = Integer(0, help="value of progress")
    
    def __init__(self, capacity):
        self._display_id = hexlify(os.urandom(8)).decode('ascii')
        
    def _repr_html_(self):
        return "<progress max='{}' value='{}'></progress>".format(self.capacity, self.progress)
    
    def display(self):
        display_with_id(self, display_id=self._display_id)
    
    @observe('capacity', 'progress')
    def update(self, change):
        update_display(self, display_id=self._display_id)
```

@The-Funk, in Ubuntu 16.04, when apt gets **any** HTTP error code for the `InRelease` file, apt would then look for a Release file. However, apt was updated (see https://github.com/Debian/apt/commit/cbbf185c3c55effe47f218a07e7b1f324973a8a6 for the specific commit) so that it would only happen for HTTP 404 errors. So even though they are both apt, one is newer than the other :smile:.

It might be worth making a commit for apt that fixes this, because I can imagine some other repos might still not be using `InRelease` files and are configured to give 403 errors instead of 404 Errors for security reasons (like this one). 

@dorodnic, it might just be easier to make an `InRelease` file for the repo, (see [here](https://help.ubuntu.com/community/CreateAuthenticatedRepository) for the guide), especially since most Ubuntu 16.04 LTS users would start switching over to 18.04 LTS at the end of this month, which has an updated version of `apt`.

You should just need to run one command, `gpg --clearsign -o InRelease Release` and that should make the `InRelease` file (assuming the instructions in the above link are accurate). And that should fix it for everyone that has an apt that's been updated since 2017.

