By the way: I noticed this issue in one of my projects where I had been using a ``py::capule``-based module shutdown handler similar to what we currently describe [in the documentation](http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/misc.html#module-destructors). The trouble with that approach is that instances of classes defined within the module may still be alive when the shutdown handler is called. 

I thus switched to something like the following
```cpp
py::cpp_function cleanup_callback(
    [](py::handle weakref) {
        /* ... shutdown logic .. */
        weakref.dec_ref();
    }
);
(void) py::weakref(m.attr("BaseClass"), cleanup_callback).release();
```
and was surprised that it stopped getting called as soon as any ``BaseClass``-derived instance was created.

In any case, now that this is fixed, it might be worth mentioning this alternative destruction logic in the docs.

